<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,738,1846]" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1569,1594]" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">Remarks.</emphasis>
Based on the greatly inflated gonostylus, the new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xu &amp; Shi &amp; Huang &amp; Wu" authorityYear="2017" box="[1124,1277,1569,1593]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Mohrigia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cylindrata">
<emphasis box="[1124,1277,1569,1593]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">M. cylindrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1294,1365,1569,1594]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1952,1974]" captionTargetBox="[151,1402,217,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mohrigia cylindrata sp. nov., male, holotype. A, left gonostylus, ventral view; B, part of hypopygium, ventral view; C, palps, lateral view; D, 4 th flagellomere, lateral view; E, apex of foretibia, posteroventral view. Scale bar = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/837161/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">Figs 2</figureCitation>
A, B). However, the new species can be diagnosed in having its gonostylus more inflated and nearly spherical, and the dorsal medial margin of gonostylus less expanded, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xu &amp; Shi &amp; Huang &amp; Wu" authorityYear="2017" box="[816,971,1641,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Mohrigia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cylindrata">
<emphasis box="[816,971,1641,1665]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">M. cylindrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the gonostylus ovate and the dorsal medial margin strongly expanded. Furthermore, the tegmen of the new species is triangular and a finger-like process exists at the apex of the central strip, while it is evenly curved towards the top and without the finger-like structure in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xu &amp; Shi &amp; Huang &amp; Wu" authorityYear="2017" box="[284,437,1749,1773]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Mohrigia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cylindrata">
<emphasis box="[284,437,1749,1773]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">M. cylindrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="77" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,738,1846]" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1785,1810]" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after its nearly spherical gonostylus, from the Latin adjective 
<emphasis box="[1308,1429,1785,1809]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="77">globulosus</emphasis>
, meaning spherical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
